> Thanks for taking the time to report this.
> Can you please attach an example that shows the issue or missing feature?  (Must be openly licensed, completely self-contained so can directly run what you provide. Ideally use test_regress format, see https://veripool.org/guide/latest/contributing.html?highlight=test_regress#reporting-bugs)

Here is code that reproduces the bug

```sv
module top;
    logic [7:0] b = 8'hA5;
    logic [31:0] y;

    // The problematic assignment
    always_comb begin
        y = {<<{b}};  // Should place result in MSBs, zeros in LSBs
    end

    initial begin
        #10; 

        $display("Input b = %h (%b)", b, b);
        $display("Output y = %h (%b)", y, y);
        $display("");
        $display("According to IEEE 1800-2023:");
        $display("  Stream should be in MSBs: %h", {b, 24'b0});
        $display("  Zeros should be in LSBs");
        $display("");
        $display("Verilator result: %h", y);
        $display("Expected result:  %h", {b, 24'b0});
        $display("");

        if (y == {b, 24'b0}) begin
            $display("PASS: Verilator is correct");
        end else begin
            $display("FAIL: Verilator bug - stream placed in LSBs instead of MSBs");
            $display("   Got: %h", y);
            $display("   Expected: %h", {b, 24'b0});
        end

        $finish;
    end
endmodule
```

> What output from that test indicates it is wrong, and what is the correct or expected output?  (Or, please make test self-checking if possible.)

The IEEE 1800-2023 in 11.4.14 specifies that 
>> If the target represents a fixed-size variable that is wider than the stream, the stream shall be widened to match it by filling with zero bits on the right.

> What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?

```sh
verilator --binary --exe --build -Mdir obj_dir -sv --timing -Wno-WIDTHEXPAND top.sv && ./obj_dir/Vtop
```

> What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?  Did you try it with other simulators?

I am using git upstream version `Verilator 5.043 devel rev v5.042-59-gf32095dd1`. All other simulators I tried it on succeeded.

> What OS and distribution are you using?

Linux arch

> May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?

I think this should not be too complicated to fix, so I wouldn't mind trying to fix it.

> (Please avoid attaching screenshots that show text - you can convert images to text using e.g. https://ocr.space)

When checking for open issues that contained the word `streaming` I did not have the impression that they explicitly mentionned that the result was incorrect compared to the IEEE. Sorry if this is a duplicate.
Thanks for the work on verilator !

